MCP server configuration in Claude Code is split across two distinct scopes, and choosing the wrong one is one of the most common architectural mistakes teams make in production.

| Scope | Config file | Who sees it | Committed to VCS? | Typical use |
|:------|:------------|:------------|:-----------------:|:------------|
| **Project** | `.mcp.json` (repo root) | Every developer who clones the repo | ✅ Yes | Shared team tooling: CI databases, Jira, internal APIs |
| **User** | `~/.claude.json` | Only the local user | ❌ No | Personal experiments, local dev overrides, private tokens |

### Project-level scope (`.mcp.json`)

A `.mcp.json` file placed at the repository root is loaded automatically by Claude Code for every session opened inside that project. Because it lives in version control, it acts as **infrastructure-as-code for agent tooling**: new team members get the full tool surface the moment they clone the repo.

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "github": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-github"],
      "env": {
        "GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN": "${GITHUB_TOKEN}"
      }
    },
    "jira": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "mcp-server-jira"],
      "env": {
        "JIRA_HOST": "https://yourorg.atlassian.net",
        "JIRA_TOKEN": "${JIRA_API_TOKEN}"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

### User-level scope (`~/.claude.json`)

The global user config at `~/.claude.json` is the right home for servers that are personal, experimental, or that expose credentials you would never share. Claude Code merges both scopes at startup — project servers and user servers are both available in the same session.

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "local-postgres": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-postgres"],
      "env": {
        "POSTGRES_CONNECTION_STRING": "${LOCAL_PG_URL}"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

### Merge semantics and conflict resolution

When both scopes define a server with the **same key**, the project-level definition wins. This lets a team standardise on a shared Jira server while an individual developer cannot accidentally shadow it with a misconfigured personal version. The inverse — user overriding project — is intentionally blocked to preserve reproducibility.

### Architectural judgment

A useful heuristic: if a server's absence would break a teammate's workflow, it belongs in `.mcp.json`. If it only affects your own productivity or exposes your personal credentials, it belongs in `~/.claude.json`. Mixing these tiers is a common source of "works on my machine" bugs in agent pipelines.

This section provides production-ready configuration patterns for both scopes, with commentary on the architectural decisions embedded in each.

### Shared server configuration (`.mcp.json`)

The following example configures three shared servers for a typical product engineering team:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "github": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-github"],
      "env": {
        "GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN": "${GITHUB_TOKEN}"
      }
    },
    "jira": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "mcp-server-jira"],
      "env": {
        "JIRA_HOST": "https://acme.atlassian.net",
        "JIRA_TOKEN": "${JIRA_API_TOKEN}"
      }
    },
    "internal-api": {
      "command": "python",
      "args": ["-m", "acme_mcp_server"],
      "env": {
        "API_BASE_URL": "https://api.internal.acme.com",
        "API_KEY": "${ACME_INTERNAL_API_KEY}"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Key decisions encoded here:**
- `github` and `jira` use community servers (see Section 6) — no custom code to maintain.
- `internal-api` uses a custom Python server because it wraps a proprietary internal API with no community equivalent.
- All credentials use `${...}` expansion — the file is safe to commit.
- Server keys (`github`, `jira`, `internal-api`) are short, lowercase, and hyphen-separated — they become tool name prefixes, so brevity matters.

### Personal server configuration (`~/.claude.json`)

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "local-pg": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-postgres"],
      "env": {
        "POSTGRES_CONNECTION_STRING": "postgresql://localhost:5432/mydevdb"
      }
    },
    "experimental-llm-tools": {
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["/home/alice/projects/llm-tools-mcp/index.js"],
      "env": {
        "OPENAI_API_KEY": "${OPENAI_API_KEY}"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Key decisions:**
- `local-pg` connects to a local dev database — the connection string is not a secret, so it is inlined. If it were a staging database with a password, use `${...}`.
- `experimental-llm-tools` points to a local file path — appropriate for a server under active development that is not yet ready to share with the team.
- Neither server appears in `.mcp.json`, so teammates are unaffected.

### Lifecycle management

MCP server processes are spawned as child processes of Claude Code and are terminated when the session ends. They do not persist between sessions. This means:
- Servers with expensive startup (e.g., loading a large model) will incur that cost on every session.
- Servers that maintain in-memory state will lose it between sessions — design for statelessness or use an external store.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[Claude Code session starts]:::process --> B[Load .mcp.json]:::process
  B --> C[Load ~/.claude.json]:::process
  C --> D[Merge server configs]:::process
  D --> E[Spawn all server processes in parallel]:::process
  E --> F{All servers respond to tools/list?}:::decision
  F -->|yes| G[Session ready — full tool surface available]:::success
  F -->|timeout| H[Warn: slow/unresponsive server — partial tool surface]:::warn
  G --> I[Agent executes tasks]:::process
  I --> J[Session ends — all server processes terminated]:::process
```

Schema design is where architectural judgment matters most. A poorly designed schema either forces the model to fabricate values (over-constrained) or produces sparse, unreliable output (under-constrained).

### Optional fields prevent fabrication

The single most important schema design rule: **make a field optional (nullable) whenever the source document may not contain that information.**

When a field is `required` and the document does not contain the value, the model faces a dilemma: violate the schema (impossible with tool use) or invent a plausible value. It will invent. This is not hallucination in the colloquial sense — it is a rational response to an impossible constraint.

**Pattern:** Use `"type": ["string", "null"]` (a JSON Schema union type) for optional string fields, and omit the field from the `required` array.

```json
{
  "properties": {
    "po_number":    {"type": "string"},
    "delivery_date": {
      "type": ["string", "null"],
      "description": "Expected delivery date in ISO 8601 format, or null if not specified"
    }
  },
  "required": ["po_number"]
}
```

With this schema, if the document has no delivery date, the model returns `"delivery_date": null` — a clean, explicit signal of absence rather than a fabricated date.

### Enum values for ambiguity and extensibility

Enum fields constrain the model to a known vocabulary, which is excellent for downstream filtering and analytics. But real-world documents contain categories you did not anticipate. The solution is a two-field pattern:

1. A primary enum field that includes `"unclear"` (for genuinely ambiguous cases) and `"other"` (for out-of-vocabulary cases).
2. A companion `_detail` string field (optional) for free-text elaboration when the primary value is `"other"` or `"unclear"`.

```json
{
  "properties": {
    "payment_method": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["wire_transfer", "check", "credit_card", "ACH", "crypto", "unclear", "other"],
      "description": "Method of payment. Use 'unclear' if the document mentions payment but the method is ambiguous. Use 'other' for methods not in this list."
    },
    "payment_method_detail": {
      "type": ["string", "null"],
      "description": "Required when payment_method is 'other' or 'unclear'. Provide the raw text from the document."
    }
  },
  "required": ["payment_method"]
}
```

This pattern gives you:
- **Structured filtering** on the enum values for the 95% case.
- **Lossless capture** of edge cases via the detail field.
- **Explicit ambiguity signaling** via `"unclear"` — downstream systems can route these for human review.

### Required field checklist

Before marking a field `required`, ask:

| Question | If YES → | If NO → |
|:---------|:---------|:--------|
| Is this field always present in every source document? | `required` | optional / nullable |
| Can the model determine this value from context alone (without the document)? | Consider removing it | Keep as optional |
| Will a `null` value break the downstream consumer? | `required` + add a prompt instruction | optional + handle null downstream |
| Is the field a primary key or routing signal? | `required` | optional |

### Nested objects and arrays

For line-item extraction (e.g., invoice line items), use a JSON Schema `array` of objects. Each item in the array should follow the same required/optional discipline:

```json
{
  "line_items": {
    "type": "array",
    "items": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "description": {"type": "string"},
        "quantity":    {"type": "number"},
        "unit_price":  {"type": "number"},
        "line_total":  {"type": ["number", "null"]}
      },
      "required": ["description", "quantity", "unit_price"]
    }
  }
}
```

Note that `line_total` is optional here — the model may not always be able to compute it reliably, and fabricated totals are dangerous (see the next section on semantic errors).
